[3]
Date: Fri 4 Jun 2010
Source: The Mainichi Daily News [edited]
<http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20100604p2g00m0dm001000c.html>


Bans on livestock transfer lifted for part of Miyazaki
-----------------------------------------------------
The Miyazaki prefectural government said Thursday [3 Jun 2010] a
safety study has found no signs of FMD among animals in Ebino and
later lifted transfer bans on livestock in the city and vicinity,
though the spread of the contagious disease remains unlikely to stop
in other parts of the southwestern prefecture.

The bans on moving livestock within a 10-km [6.2-mile] radius from
the 4 disease-hit farms and on taking animals out of a 20-km
[12.4-mile] radius, which cover some areas in neighboring Kumamoto
and Kagoshima prefectures, was lifted midnight Thursday [3 Jun 2010],
officials said.

In the inland city, no animal has tested positive for the disease
since the last suspected infection case was confirmed 13 May 2010,
and the central and prefectural governments reached the conclusion at
the end of an 11-day safety study that began on 24 May 2010, they
said.

Since the disease broke out in Ebino on 28 Apr 2010, more than 600
cows and pigs have been slaughtered.

In the safety study, about 1300 cows at all the roughly 150 farms
located within a 3-km [1.86-mile] radius of the farms of origin have
been confirmed uninfected with the disease through antibody testing
of their blood samples, and so were pigs.

Since Monday [31 May 2010], some 97 000 cows and pigs at about 400
farms in a 3- to 10-km radius have had their condition visually
checked by veterinarians.

The prefectural government put the data together and consulted with
the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fishers before deciding on
lifting the bans, the officials said.

